Southern African Development Community (SADC) organ on Politics, Defence and Security has arrived in Eswatini for a fact-finding mission. The team was invited by the Minister for Foreign Affairs and International Cooperation Thuli Dladla on Friday. Acting Prime Minister Themba Masuku welcomed the team on Sunday to the Kingdom. The mission is led by Botswana Minister of International Affairs Dr. Lemohang Kwape, representing Troika chairperson Mokgweetsi Masisi. Upon arrival, the head of mission Kwape said the team will have a discussion with the government before interacting with the citizens. “We will interact with the government and then proceed to interact with civil society,” Kwape said. He added that the team stands ready to support the people of the Kingdom of Eswatini in their quest to bring peace and calm that will lead to socio-economic development. “SADC stands ready to support the people of the Kingdom of Eswatini in their quest to bring peace and calm that will lead to the socio-economic development of this country, something that we in the region cherish,” Kwape said. Eswatini (formerly known as Swaziland) witnessed protest as people demanded major constitutional reforms. The protesters have been calling for King Mswati to make way as part of democratic reforms, including free elections. The Acting PM said on Saturday that more than 5,000 jobs have been lost in the country following the protests witnessed in the country. Masuku toured the business property that was destroyed in Matsapha during protests earlier this week. The government has estimated the national damage at close to 3 billion Euros. On Friday, the government of the Kingdom of Eswatini condemned the acts of looting that have been witnessed during ongoing protests.